\n| genre = [[Romance film|Romance]] <br> [[Comedy film|Comedy]]<br> [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]<br> Historical <br> Time Travel\n| country = [[Thailand]]\n| language = [[Thai language|Thai]]\n| director = Pawat Panangkasri\n| based_on = ''Bupphesanniwat'' by [[Rompaeng]]\n| writer = Salaya Sukanivatt\n| producer = Arunocha Bhanubandhu\n| starring = [[Ranee Campen]]<br /> Thanavat Vatthanaputi<br /> Louis Scott<br /> Susira Nanna<br />Parama Imanothai\n| location = \n| company = Broadcast Thai Television\n| distributor = \n| channel = [[Channel 3 (Thailand)|Channel 3]]\n| picture_format = [[High-definition television|High-definition]] (HDTV) [[1080i]] [[16:9]]\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital]]\n| runtime = 150 minutes\n| first_aired = February 21, 2018\n| last_aired = April 11, 2018\n| num_episodes = 15 + 3 special episodes\n| related = \n}}\n\n'''''Love Destiny''''' ({{lang-th|[[:wikt:\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a|\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a]]}}; {{RTGS|''Bupphesanniwat''}}; {{IPA-th|b\u00f9p.p\u02b0e\u02d0.s\u01cen.n\u00ed.w\u00e2:t|IPA}}) is a [[Thailand|Thai]] historical television series that originally aired on [[Channel 3 (Thailand)|Channel 3]] from February 21, to April 11, 2018. The series contains elements of [[Romance film|romance]], [[Comedy film|comedy]] and time travel.<ref>https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/prisoners-in-thailand-get-to-watch-mega-drama-hit-love-destiny-by-popular-demand</ref><ref>http://www.nationmultimedia.com/detail/opinion/30342872</ref> Starring [[Ranee Campen]] and Thanavat Vatthanaputi, ''Love Destiny'' was a major hit in Thailand and gained popularity across Asia, contributing in a rise of tourists in filming locations.<ref>https://theculturetrip.com/asia/thailand/articles/love-destiny-the-kitsch-period-drama-taking-thailand-by-storm/</ref> Success factors were attributed to its elaborate screenplay, costumes, and locations.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-politics-costume/venerating-the-past-traditional-costume-fever-grips-thailand-idUSKBN1HF04S</ref>\n\nThe ''Lakorn'', set in [[Ayutthaya Kingdom]], during the reign of King [[Narai]] is an adaptation of the novel of the same name by [[Rompaeng]], the penname of Chanyawi Somprida.<ref>\u201c\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e41\u0e1e\u0e07 \u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e43\u0e04\u0e23? \u0e43\u0e22\u0e04\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e39\u0e49\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u201d, http://www.newtv.co.th/news/12576, accessed March 29,2018.</ref> The novel got the Seven book award in 2010 and was adapted into a television drama for the first time in this series. The television adaptation was done by Broadcast Thai Television, script-written by Sanlaya and directed by Pawat Panangsiri.<ref>^\u201c\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a\u201d, http://www.ch3thailand.com/\u0e25\u0e30\u0e04\u0e23\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e073/second/477/\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a.html, accessed March 29,2018.</ref>.\n\n==Synopsis==\nKaraket (\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e01\u0e14), a daughter of the ruler of the northern city of [[Phitsanulok Province|Phitsanulok]], lives in [[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya Province|Ayutthaya]], the capital of the [[Ayutthaya Kingdom]], during the reign of King [[Narai]] (1656\u20131688). She lives in the residence of King Narai's chief astrologer, who holds the noble title of [[Phra Horathibodi|Chaophraya Horathibodi]] (\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e22\u0e32\u0e42\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e1a\u0e14\u0e35) and is the father of her fianc\u00e9, [[Khun Si Wisan Wacha|Det]] (\u0e40\u0e14\u0e0a), a foreign ministry official holding the noble title of Muen Sunthon Thewa (\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e37\u0e48\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e40\u0e17\u0e27\u0e32).\n\nOne day, Karaket orders her attendants, Phin (\u0e1c\u0e34\u0e19) and Yaem (\u0e41\u0e22\u0e49\u0e21), to capsize the boat of her love rival, Lady Chanwat (\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e27\u0e32\u0e14), a daughter of [[Kosa Lek|Lek]] (\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e47\u0e01), the foreign minister holding the noble title of Chaophraya Kosathibodi (\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e22\u0e32\u0e42\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e1a\u0e14\u0e35). Chanwat survives, but a maidservant of her dies in the incident. As everyone suspects Karaket, Chaophraya Horathibodi recites the [[Krishna|Kritsana]]-[[Kali]] mantra (\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e01\u0e24\u0e29\u0e13\u0e01\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35) to find out if she really is the culprit. The mantra kills Karaket, and her soul travels forwards to the present time to meet Ketsurang (\u0e40\u0e01\u0e28\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e23\u0e32\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c), a 25-year-old woman who appears to be her twin sister and has just died in a car accident. Karaket asks Ketsurang to assume her body and do good deeds to turn over a new leaf.\n\nAs Ketsurang wakes up in Karaket's body, she finds that all the people around her hate her because of Ketsurang's evil acts in the past. In Ayutthaya, she befriends many historical figures, including [[Kosa Pan|Pan]] (\u0e1b\u0e32\u0e19), Lek's younger brother who holds the noble title of Phra Wisut Sunthon (\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23), and [[Maria Guyomar de Pinha]], a Japanese\u2013Portuguese woman whom [[Constantine Phaulkon]], a Greek adventurer and King Narai's minister, falls in love with. She also finds that Rueang (\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07), Det's comrade who holds the noble title of Muen Rueang Ratchaphakdi (\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e37\u0e48\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e20\u0e31\u0e01\u0e14\u0e35), looks so much like Rueangrit (\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e24\u0e17\u0e18\u0e34\u0e4c), her boyfriend in the present day, thus feeling closely acquainted with him.\n\nThe eccentric and goofy behaviour of a modern-day woman like Ketsurang shocks everyone, but her kindness makes them change their attitude towards her, winning their hearts and minds eventually. As for Det, despite suspecting her strangely changed behaviour and believing that a ghost is possessing her, he finds himself deep in love with her, whilst Ketsurang herself also finds that she has developed romantic feelings for him, much to the dismay of Karaket's ghost. To appease Karaket, Ketsurang refuses to marry Det. But Karaket later changes her mind and blesses their marriage as the good deeds Ketsurang has performed allows Karaket to leave the afterlife for a [[Rebirth (Buddhism)|rebirth]].\n\nMeanwhile, Rueang is promoted to the title of Khun Rueang Aphai Phakdi (\u0e02\u0e38\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2d\u0e20\u0e31\u0e22\u0e20\u0e31\u0e01\u0e14\u0e35) and tries to win the heart of Lady Chanwat, whose father, Lek, has been charged with corruption and punished to death according to complaints from Phaulkon. Rueang manages to gain favour from Chanwat's mother, Lady Nim (\u0e19\u0e34\u0e48\u0e21), who disdains his low race, and later gets promoted to Phra Ram Narong (\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21\u0e13\u0e23\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c).\n\nDet also gets promoted to a higher rank, obtaining the title of Khun Si Wisan Wacha (\u0e02\u0e38\u0e19\u0e28\u0e23\u0e35\u0e27\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e25\u0e27\u0e32\u0e08\u0e32), and is appointed to an [[Siamese embassy to France (1686)|Ayutthayan embassy]] accredited to the court of King [[Louis XIV]] of France, with Pan as ambassador. After returning to Ayutthaya from France, he gets promoted to Phra Si Wisan Sunthon (\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e25\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23). Det, Rueang, and Pan later join the [[Siamese revolution of 1688|successful enterprise]] of [[Phetracha|Phra Phet Racha]], King Narai's xenophobic regent, to seize power and get rid of the Christians in the kingdom. The coup is supported by the Buddhist clergy and Narai's own daughter, Princess [[Sudawadi]], and leads to the execution of Phaulkon.\n\nKetsurang later discovers a [[Samut khoi|folding book]] containing the Kritsana-Kali mantra. As she touches it, her soul flies out of Karaket's body and returns to the present, where she finds that her boyfriend, Rueangrit, has blamed himself for her death during the car accident and has decided to enter the monkhood for life in dedication to her. Ketsurang then sees the shadow of Det in the body of Rueangrit and learns that Rueangrit is actually a rebirth of Det who has been reborn to marry her for many lives, thus realising that they are destined to be together. Suddenly, she hears the Kritsana-Kali mantra, which everyone at the residence of Chaophraya Horathibodi has been chanting for days in order to help her return to the body. As she wakes up again, Det hugs her tight, telling her that he loves her no matter who she is or where she was from.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main ===\n* [[Ranee Campen]] as Ketsurang/Karaket\n* [[Thanavat Wattanaputi]] as [[Khun Si Wisan Wacha|Det]], son of Chaophraya Horathibodi and Champa\n* [[Louis Scott (actor)|Louis Scott]] as [[Constantine Phaulkon|Constantine Phaulkon]]\n* [[Susira Nanna]] as [[Maria Guyomar de Pinha]], Phaulkon's wife\n* [[Parama Imanothai]] as Rueang/Rueangrit\n* [[Kannarun Wongkajornklai]] as Lady Chanwat, daughter of Lek and Nim\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Praptpadol Suwanbang]] as King [[Narai]]\n* [[Sarut Vijittranon]] as [[Phetracha|Phra Phet Racha]], Narai's regent\n* [[Jirayu Tantrakul]] as [[Suriyenthrathibodi|Luang Sorasak]], Phra Phet Racha's son\n* [[Nirut Sirijanya]] as [[Phra Horathibodi|Chaophraya Horathibodi]], Narai's chief astrologer\n* [[Chamaiporn Jaturaput]] as Lady Champa, Chaophraya Horathibodi's wife\n* [[Surasak Chaiat]] as Lek, Narai's foreign minister\n* [[Chartchai Ngamsan]] as [[Kosa Pan|Pan]], Lek's younger brother\n* [[Rachanee Siralert]] as Lady Nim, Lek's wife\n* [[Ampha Phoosit]] as Prik, Champa's attendant\n* [[Vimon Panchalijunha]] as Chuan, Champa's attendant\n* [[Janya Thanasawaangkoun]] as Phin, Karaket's attendant\n* [[Ramida Prapatsanobon]] as Yaem, Karaket's attendant\n* [[Witsarut Himmarat]] as Choi, Det's attendant\n\n===Cameos===\n* [[Paweena Chariffsakul]] as Ketsurang's mother\n* [[Banjerdsri Yamabhaya]] as Ketsurang's grandmother\n* [[Tachaya Prathumwan]] as [[Phra Pi]], Narai's adopted son\n* [[Natanop Chuenhirun]] as [[Si Prat]], Det's older brother\n* [[Thongkao Pattarachokechai]] as Maria's father\n* [[Suzana Renaud]] as Clara, Maria's attendant\n* [[Wariya Thaisaet]] as Claudia, Maria's attendant\n* [[Watcharachai Sunthornsiri]] as Achan Chi Pa Khao (White-Robed Master)\n* [[Wiksawaweet Wongwannlop]] as Luang Si Yot, Narai's minister\n* [[Peter Tuinstra]] as [[Simon de la Loub\u00e8re]]\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Rating ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Episode \n! scope=\"col\" | Bangkok\n! scope=\"col\" | Nationwide\n! scope=\"col\" | Urban\n! scope=\"col\" | Rural\n|-\n|21-02-2018\t||1\t||5.80\t||3.40\t||4.60\t||2.40\n|-\n|22-02-2018\t||2\t||7.50\t||4.80\t||5.70\t||3.80\n|-\n|28-02-2018\t||3\t||11.60\t||7.30\t||9.30\t||5.60\n|-\n|01-03-2018\t||4\t||13.00\t||8.20\t||10.00\t||6.40\n|-\n|07-03-2018\t||5\t||16.00\t||11.40\t||13.00\t||9.70\n|-\n|08-03-2018\t||6\t||19.80\t||12.60\t||14.30\t||10.40\n|-\n|14-03-2018\t||7\t||20.50\t||14.80\t||17.80\t||12.30\n|-\n|15-03-2018\t||8\t||22.80\t||15.50\t||18.50\t||12.70\n|-\n|21-03-2018\t||9\t||23.40\t||16.00\t||19.60\t||13.00\n|-\n|22-03-2018\t||10\t||21.40\t||16.00\t||20.20\t||13.20\n|-\n|28-03-2018\t||11\t||22.60\t||17.40\t||20.60\t||15.10\n|-\n|29-03-2018\t||12\t||23.90\t||17.40\t||19.80\t||15.00\n|-\n|04-04-2018\t||13\t||21.80\t||17.40\t||21.80\t||14.80\n|-\n|05-04-2018\t||14\t||23.90\t||17.90\t||20.90\t||15.40\n|-\n|11-04-2018\t||15\t||23.40\t||18.60\t||22.80\t||16.10\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" | Average:\t||18.50\t||13.30\t||15.90\t||11.10\n|}\n\n====Specials====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Episode \n! scope=\"col\" | Bangkok\n! scope=\"col\" | Nationwide\n! scope=\"col\" | Urban\n! scope=\"col\" | Rural\n|-\n|12-04-2018\t||Sp.1\t||12.60\t||10.10\t||12.40\t||8.60\n|-\n|18-04-2018\t||Sp.2\t||12.30\t||8.60\t||11.50\t||6.70\n|-\n|19-04-2018\t||Sp.3\t||12.50\t||8.00\t||10.60\t||6.30\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" | Average:\t||12.50\t||9.10\t||11.50\t||7.20\n|}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n* \"Bupphesanniwat\" (\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a), opening theme by [[Saranyu Winaipanit]]\n* \"Phiang Sop Ta\" (\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e1a\u0e15\u0e32; Just Eye Contact), ending theme by [[Lydia Sarunrat|Sarunrat Dean]]\n* \"Ochao Oei\" (\u0e2d\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e22; \"Thou Oh Thou\") by [[Pete Pol]]\n** Special version by Thanavat Vatthanaputi\n* \"Thoe No Thoe\" (\u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d; \"You Oh You\") by Wathiya Ruangnirat\n** Special version by Ranee Campen\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ch3thailand.com/\u0e25\u0e30\u0e04\u0e23\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e073/second/477/\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e19\u0e34\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a.html}} {{in lang|th}}\n\n[[Category:Thai historical television series]]\n", "name_user": "Miteix", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Destiny_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "James Victor (actor)", "text_new": "'''Lincoln Peralta''' (July 27, 1939 \u2013 June 20, 2016), known professionally as '''James Victor''', was a Dominican-born American actor. He was best known for his role of Sgt. Jaime Mendoza on ''[[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1990)|The Family Channel]]'' television series, ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'', from 1990 to 1993 for three seasons.<ref name=thr>{{cite news|first=Mike|last=Barnes |title=James Victor, Cassavetes Protege and 'Zorro' Actor, Dies at 76 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-victor-dead-zorro-actor-908070 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2016-07-02 |accessdate=2016-07-10}}</ref> Victor was a longtime protege of filmmaker [[John Cassavetes]]. He appeared in several of Cassavetes' films, including ''[[Shadows (1959 film)|Shadows]]'' (1959), ''[[Too Late Blues]]'' (1961), and ''[[Faces (1968 film)|Faces]]'' (1968).<ref name=thr/>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nVictor, the youngest of his family's six children, was born '''Lincoln Peralta''' in [[Santiago de los Caballeros, Dominican Republic]], on July 27, 1939.<ref name=thr/> He emigrated from the [[Dominican Republic]] to [[New York City]] with his family when he was four years old. He would later chose the stage name \"James Victor\" in honor of his older brother.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn 1958, Victor graduated from the now defunct [[Haaren High School]] in the [[Hell's Kitchen]] section of [[Midtown Manhattan]].<ref name=thr/> He got a job in the [[mailroom]] of the [[Walt Disney Company]]'s New York City offices and joined [[El Nuevo C\u00edrculo Dramatico]], a bilingual [[theater company]], after graduating from high school.<ref name=thr/>\n\nBy chance, Victor met [[John Cassavetes]], who would become a personal and professional mentor. The meeting led Victor to study at an acting workshop which had been established by Cassavetes and Burt Lane, a [[theater director]] and acting coach.<ref name=thr/> Cassavetes liked Victor's work and cast him in several of his films, including ''[[Shadows (1959 film)|Shadows]]'' in 1959, ''[[Too Late Blues]]'' in 1961, and ''[[Faces (1968 film)|Faces]]'' in 1968. Victor called Cassavetes his \"[[:wikt:godfather|godfather]]\" and the friendship between the two continued until Cassavetes' death in 1989.<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Television===\nIn 1962, both Victor and Cassavetes guest starred on an episode of ''[[The Lloyd Bridges Show]]''.<ref name=thr/> Victor's television credits during the 1960s to the 1980s included guest spots on ''[[My Three Sons]]'', ''[[I Spy (1965 TV series)|I Spy]]'', ''[[Family Affair]]'', ''[[Adam-12]]'', [[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]], ''[[The White Shadow (TV series)|The White Shadow]]'', ''[[Falcon Crest]]'', ''[[Remington Steele]]'' and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn addition to his guest television spots, Victor was a full cast member on three series on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] during the 1970s and 1980s. In 1976, Victor appeared on the short-lived ABC summertime replacement, ''[[Viva Valdez]]'', a show about the Valdezs, a Mexican-American family who operate a plumbing business in [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]].<ref name=thr/> He next co-starred in 1983 television [[sitcom]], ''[[Condo (TV series)|Condo]]'', which starred [[McLean Stevenson]] and [[Luis \u00c1valos]], playing the grandfather of a Hispanic family. Victor also played the grandfather of [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]]'s character on ''[[I Married Dora]]'', which aired on ABC from 1987 to 1988.<ref name=thr/>\n\nHe became best known for his starring role as Sgt. Jaime Mendoza on ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'' for four seasons from 1990 to 1993.\n\n===Film===\nIn addition to his earlier film work with Cassavetes, Victor appeared opposite William Devane in ''[[Rolling Thunder (film)|Rolling Thunder]]'' in 1977, ''[[Borderline (1980 film)|Borderline]]'' in 1980, and ''[[Losin' It]]'' in 1983.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn ''[[Stand and Deliver]]'' (1988), a [[biopic]] about teacher [[Jaime Escalante]] starring [[Edward James Olmos]], Victor played the father of one of Esclannte's students. Victor's character opposed Escalante's efforts to encourage his daughter to attend college.<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Theater===\nIn 1986, Victor starred in ''I Don't Have to Show You No Stinking Badges!'', a satirical play by [[playwright]] [[Luis Valdez]], during its premiere and original run at the [[Los Angeles Theatre Center]].<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Later life===\nVictor, who suffered from heart disease, died at his apartment in [[Hollywood]], on June 20, 2016, at the age of 76. He was survived by several aunts, cousins, nieces and nephews. Victor was buried in the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] on July 10, 2016.<ref name=thr/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1968|| ''[[Girl in Gold Boots]]'' || Joey ||\n|-\n|1972|| ''[[Fuzz (film)|Fuzz]]'' || Patrolman Gomez ||\n|-\n|1977|| ''[[Rolling Thunder (film)|Rolling Thunder]]'' || Lopez ||\n|-\n|1979|| ''[[Boulevard Nights]]'' || Gil Moreno ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Defiance (1980 film)|Defiance]]'' || Father Rivera ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Borderline (1980 film)|Borderline]]'' || Mirandez ||\n|-\n|1983|| ''[[Losin' It]]'' || Lawyer ||\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[The Telephone (1988 film)|The Telephone]]'' || Big Ray on Answering Machine || Voice\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[Stand and Deliver]]'' || Ana's Father ||\n|-\n|1995|| ''[[Gunfighter's Moon]]'' || Juan Acosta ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''Ray of Sunshine'' || ||\n|-\n|2012|| ''[[Casa de mi padre]]'' || Old Friend #3 ||\n|-\n|2012|| ''[[Bless Me, Ultima (film)|Bless Me, Ultima]]'' || Antonio's Grandfather || (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|id=0896116|name=James Victor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victor, James}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago de los Caballeros]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Haaren High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Lincoln Peralta''' (July 27, 1939 \u2013 June 20, 2016), known professionally as '''James Victor''', was a Dominican-born American actor. He was best known for his role of Sgt. Jaime Mendoza on ''[[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1980)|The Family Channel]]'' television series, ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'', from 1990 to 1993 for three seasons.<ref name=thr>{{cite news|first=Mike|last=Barnes |title=James Victor, Cassavetes Protege and 'Zorro' Actor, Dies at 76 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-victor-dead-zorro-actor-908070 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2016-07-02 |accessdate=2016-07-10}}</ref> Victor was a longtime protege of filmmaker [[John Cassavetes]]. He appeared in several of Cassavetes' films, including ''[[Shadows (1959 film)|Shadows]]'' (1959), ''[[Too Late Blues]]'' (1961), and ''[[Faces (1968 film)|Faces]]'' (1968).<ref name=thr/>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nVictor, the youngest of his family's six children, was born '''Lincoln Peralta''' in [[Santiago de los Caballeros, Dominican Republic]], on July 27, 1939.<ref name=thr/> He emigrated from the [[Dominican Republic]] to [[New York City]] with his family when he was four years old. He would later chose the stage name \"James Victor\" in honor of his older brother.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn 1958, Victor graduated from the now defunct [[Haaren High School]] in the [[Hell's Kitchen]] section of [[Midtown Manhattan]].<ref name=thr/> He got a job in the [[mailroom]] of the [[Walt Disney Company]]'s New York City offices and joined [[El Nuevo C\u00edrculo Dramatico]], a bilingual [[theater company]], after graduating from high school.<ref name=thr/>\n\nBy chance, Victor met [[John Cassavetes]], who would become a personal and professional mentor. The meeting led Victor to study at an acting workshop which had been established by Cassavetes and Burt Lane, a [[theater director]] and acting coach.<ref name=thr/> Cassavetes liked Victor's work and cast him in several of his films, including ''[[Shadows (1959 film)|Shadows]]'' in 1959, ''[[Too Late Blues]]'' in 1961, and ''[[Faces (1968 film)|Faces]]'' in 1968. Victor called Cassavetes his \"[[:wikt:godfather|godfather]]\" and the friendship between the two continued until Cassavetes' death in 1989.<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Television===\nIn 1962, both Victor and Cassavetes guest starred on an episode of ''[[The Lloyd Bridges Show]]''.<ref name=thr/> Victor's television credits during the 1960s to the 1980s included guest spots on ''[[My Three Sons]]'', ''[[I Spy (1965 TV series)|I Spy]]'', ''[[Family Affair]]'', ''[[Adam-12]]'', [[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]], ''[[The White Shadow (TV series)|The White Shadow]]'', ''[[Falcon Crest]]'', ''[[Remington Steele]]'' and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn addition to his guest television spots, Victor was a full cast member on three series on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] during the 1970s and 1980s. In 1976, Victor appeared on the short-lived ABC summertime replacement, ''[[Viva Valdez]]'', a show about the Valdezs, a Mexican-American family who operate a plumbing business in [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]].<ref name=thr/> He next co-starred in 1983 television [[sitcom]], ''[[Condo (TV series)|Condo]]'', which starred [[McLean Stevenson]] and [[Luis \u00c1valos]], playing the grandfather of a Hispanic family. Victor also played the grandfather of [[Elizabeth Pe\u00f1a]]'s character on ''[[I Married Dora]]'', which aired on ABC from 1987 to 1988.<ref name=thr/>\n\nHe became best known for his starring role as Sgt. Jaime Mendoza on ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'' for four seasons from 1990 to 1993.\n\n===Film===\nIn addition to his earlier film work with Cassavetes, Victor appeared opposite William Devane in ''[[Rolling Thunder (film)|Rolling Thunder]]'' in 1977, ''[[Borderline (1980 film)|Borderline]]'' in 1980, and ''[[Losin' It]]'' in 1983.<ref name=thr/>\n\nIn ''[[Stand and Deliver]]'' (1988), a [[biopic]] about teacher [[Jaime Escalante]] starring [[Edward James Olmos]], Victor played the father of one of Esclannte's students. Victor's character opposed Escalante's efforts to encourage his daughter to attend college.<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Theater===\nIn 1986, Victor starred in ''I Don't Have to Show You No Stinking Badges!'', a satirical play by [[playwright]] [[Luis Valdez]], during its premiere and original run at the [[Los Angeles Theatre Center]].<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Later life===\nVictor, who suffered from heart disease, died at his apartment in [[Hollywood]], on June 20, 2016, at the age of 76. He was survived by several aunts, cousins, nieces and nephews. Victor was buried in the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] on July 10, 2016.<ref name=thr/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1968|| ''[[Girl in Gold Boots]]'' || Joey ||\n|-\n|1972|| ''[[Fuzz (film)|Fuzz]]'' || Patrolman Gomez ||\n|-\n|1977|| ''[[Rolling Thunder (film)|Rolling Thunder]]'' || Lopez ||\n|-\n|1979|| ''[[Boulevard Nights]]'' || Gil Moreno ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Defiance (1980 film)|Defiance]]'' || Father Rivera ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Borderline (1980 film)|Borderline]]'' || Mirandez ||\n|-\n|1983|| ''[[Losin' It]]'' || Lawyer ||\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[The Telephone (1988 film)|The Telephone]]'' || Big Ray on Answering Machine || Voice\n|-\n|1988|| ''[[Stand and Deliver]]'' || Ana's Father ||\n|-\n|1995|| ''[[Gunfighter's Moon]]'' || Juan Acosta ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''Ray of Sunshine'' || ||\n|-\n|2012|| ''[